The ambiguity of which version is the  thing that some articles do for no real reason. However, in order for the ambiguity to work three things must be true:

The ambiguity must be ambiguous. People should be genially unable to decide which version of the article is the true one, no matter how hard they think or how many times they reread the article. 046 does this part reasonably well.
The competing versions must be different enough. Making two versions of SCP-076, one of which describes Able as wearing a red shirt, and another - a blue shirt, wouldn't work, because I don't care at all what kind of shirt Able wears. In case of 046, the plant thing acts more or less the same in both versions - it attracts prey, then dissolves it. The only difference is whether or not the prey is willing. Maybe for some people that's enough of a difference, I don't know, but for me both versions are pretty much identical.
At least one version, preferably both, must be interesting enough on its own. That is the point where 046 fails the most for me. It's a plant what dissolves animals. It doesn't look very weird, doesn't act unexpectedly, doesn't have some secret agenda or old history with sinister implications. It's just boring. And juggling several boring things isn't very interesting, no matter how impressively you juggle. That's why they put those things on fire at circus.






